    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Thanks for bringing this up! This is not a bug but a feature of Solidity we decided to use. Let me clarify.\r\n\r\nSince the contracts are designed to use multiple inheritance, they need to be defined like this because otherwise the base constructor can be called different times with different arguments. There is no warning when this happens, as seen in [this example](https://remix.ethereum.org/#version=soljson-v0.4.16+commit.d7661dd9.js&gist=db66390655e34bded256eb4300c8f825). In this case, contract `B` is making an assumption on the value of `a`, which holds if `B` itself is instantiated, but which doesn't necessarily hold for child contracts such as `D`.\r\n\r\nThis feature prevents such a bug from happening because the child contract cannot assume the constructor parameters that were used for the parent constructor.",
